{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a369f3e1-37ed-481a-baca-df03f3075ccc","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the Inspector with **npx** — no install needed:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./path/to/YourServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:6274`) that proxies stdio to your server.\n\n**From the Inspector UI you can:**\n1. **Connect** — click \"Connect\" to initialize the MCP handshake\n2. **List Tools** — browse all tools your server exposes\n3. **Call Tools** — fill in parameters and invoke them, seeing raw JSON request/response\n4. **Check Errors** — inspect stderr output and protocol-level errors\n\n**Tips for debugging:**\n- **Log to stderr**, not stdout — stdout is the MCP transport. Use `Console.Error.WriteLine()` for debug output.\n- Pass environment variables with `-e`:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector -e KEY=value dotnet run --project ./src/MyServer\n  ```\n- If your server is already built, point at the DLL directly:\n  ```bash\n  npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet exec ./bin/Debug/net8.0/MyServer.dll\n  ```\n- Add `--no-build` to `dotnet run` to skip rebuilds during iteration.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ad6202ba-8eee-426b-9b8f-ed4a70fa319f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I can answer this directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":394,"requestId":"C02A:2A497:1C88260:2027CB4:6A07C303"},"id":"3c27ada9-1907-43b7-84ae-f95d3a936a49","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:06:21.609Z","parentId":"45127dc1-390e-4882-928f-04654e6ed491"}
